metadata.name: Mur #219
metadata.description:
Mur is a series of computational drawings of stacked and falling bricks. The bricks are placed in different configurations of walls, towers, stacks and paths, and are then exposed to gravity. 

The graphics are coded with p5.js and the rigid body simulations with ammo.js. In live mode, press 's' to save a screenshot and 'e' to save a high resolution image. Press 't' to toggle textures. 

Each scene is drawn twice, first brick by brick as they fall or stay in place, then the scene as a whole. Mur is optimized for Chrome, uses WebGL and may not work in all browsers.

metadata.name: Proxima #178
metadata.description:
The preparations for the first mission began in 2142. It had become clear that mining petroleum on Earth would soon become financially unfeasible, so looking to other planets was the only logical choice. It took seventeen more years to perfect the technology so that the first colonists could reach Proxima b within the lifetime of one generation.

After 45 years of travelling at almost one-tenth of the speed of light, they reached their new home. It was rich in petrochemicals but scarce in the nutrients necessary for long term human survival. After merely six generations, humanity was forced to travel once again in search of a new world. The four missions that parted from the Proxima system to colonise other possibly habitable planets in the galaxy sparked a new age of human civilisation that would never see itself united and thriving again.

Eventually, all the colonies became independent societies as their differing interests drove them apart. Each small civilisation chose its path, wandering the void of space alone. Over time, millions of kilometres apart, each colony developed its own culture and traditions. While their habits and customs changed, some things remained the same across all the societies, like how it became a certain tradition to convert the outer world years and days to Earth time and celebrate holidays according to the calendar of the old world.

The new nomads learned from the first pilgrims. They used the technology once optimised for oil extraction to traverse other worlds, searching for sustenance. Peculiar wandering nonspaces emerged from the involuntary degrowth of human civilisation.

-----

Click on the image to open the menu. You may choose the quality from preview to the resolution of a print of approximately 30cm in height. In live mode, click on PNG to save the rendered image.
Depending on the device and CPU usage, it takes from a few seconds (on fast computers) to a minute (sometimes more) on mid-tier phones to render the image.

Requirements: 1GB of RAM. The system needs up to 200 MB of free RAM for rendering square preview images and up to 400 MB of free RAM for rendering square images at the highest resolution. We tested on Chrome, Safari, Firefox, Edge / Windows, Mac OS, Android, and iPhone, but please make sure it works on your device before minting.

Original piece by mrkswcz and Ismahelio. Made with Three.js. 

San Sebastian - Madrid. May 2022.

metadata.name: Ribbonacci #112
metadata.description:
Interlocking ribbons are placed around focal points like sunflower seeds, using the Golden angle.

Features: six color schemes, two color variation types, three rendering styles, and variable aspect ratios.

----

The Golden angle is based on φ ("phi"), the most irrational number. Using this angle between successive ribbons means that as they spiral outwards, they end up distributed evenly around the center. The Golden angle is visible in many plants, not just the sunflower, since it helps prevent leaves from shading each other. ("Fibonacci phyllotaxis")

Phi, the Golden angle, and Fibonacci numbers generally have many fascinating, unexpected, and beautiful mathematical and geometric relationships. Learning about them was a delight.

----

Keys: 1-8 to change pixel density, s or double click to save, S to toggle drop shadows if present.
URL parameters: shadows (0 or 1), animated (0 or 1), aspect (e.g. 16:9, 2:3, 8.5:11)

metadata.name: FX the 13th #2
metadata.description:
Iconography and memes are the language of our times, but they’re also culturally specific. By juxtaposing the iconic slasher with varying pastel backgrounds and objects much different from implements of death, what effect does it have on the viewer?

Through this I also want to explore how static images can leave ambiguity in the story. Both by removing context, changing it, or by adding something “ridiculous,” imagery can cause us to make assumptions and perceive things that might exist outside the image’s frame.

Is Jason attacking someone just outside the frame? Might he be snatching the bride’s bouquet at a wedding, or is he viciously murdering someone with it? Is he about to smash someone’s head in with a teddy bear, or is he protecting it from an angry dog?

The answers are up to the viewer. However, if he is attacking, then how do you respond to the idea of a supernatural serial killer attacking with these items? Are they innocuous? Do they tell you a story about what it means to die bludgeoned by a sex toy or a flyswatter? Is it funny? More terrifying? Ridiculous, scary, or both? 

What does this project say to YOU?

------
There are varying rarities with the backgrounds and masks. If you find “Rick’s Mask” you’ll earn an extra airdrop at sell-out/burn down. Find me on Twitter if you’re looking to buy one on secondary to ensure the airdrop hasn’t already happened.

There are 22 different items to be held by Jason, and all are of equal rarity.

Made with @purespider’s pfp generating code, with 10% of sales flowing there.

Minters also get assigned 33% of secondary sales. Thanks for bringing this project to life.

metadata.name: pure  #16
metadata.description:
A polygon is generated by a random number of vertices. Each polygon consists of triangles which are connected to each other. The vertices receive pure color values from Red Green Blue, which also can create Magenta Yellow Cyan as well Black and White. Each vertex also gets an opacity value.
The colors are blended between the neighboring vertices and create a unique colored polygon.
The vertices occupy specific positions in space which are reflected in the background and become observable during the rotation of the construct.
Canvas and background receive colors per token as well to create different oppositions to the object.
The polygon rotates slowly to experience a mixture of a two and three dimensional experience.
Additionally the perspective can be adjusted for a quicker rotation around the object.

metadata.name: unbuilt #201
metadata.description:
This is a journey through architecture that never existed.

Inspired by the grammatical rules behind French sacral architecture of the Middle Ages, this generative tool is meant for creating a collection of 256 plans of fictional buildings. Each plan is a unique variation on semantic relations between architectural elements: from a regular composition resembling existing churches to a dynamic aggregation of vaults, columns and chevets. But always following the same set of rules extracted from multiple examples of gothic cathedrals.

Every church has its place and time in which it could have been built in an alternative series of historical events.

This artistic tribute to the research of Stiny and Mitchell about Palladian architecture or Duarte's work about Siza takes the topic of formalizing architectural language onto a lighthearted level by moving it to a slightly imaginary world.

To zoom, press a mouse button when over the image or touch the screen. To pan, keep the mouse pressed and move it around.

Stephen Wolfram's Elementary Cellular Automaton where 3 different rules are drawn in the Red, Green and Blue color components of the image.
